    Museum of Engineering Science and Machinery
    Very interesting museum covering the history of measurements, clocks, mechanical machinery, clocks, nautical science, etc.. Highly recommend getting the audio guide (available in French, English, Spanish, Chinese, German, Japanese, and Italian). Museum is on three floors - accessible via lift or stairs. There's also a cafe on site with some light foodfare options. The displays are interesting and the ending portion inside the former church which now houses some vehicles, has a swing pendulum which is great to see. Very small giftshop - mostly books - at the end of the tour. An informative visit.
    Visited March 2024
    Traveled solo

A must see museum, especially if you like science and technology
May 2024 • Couples
This was my favorite museum on a recent trip to Paris. Housed inside a former church, the museum was much larger than I expected. The museum has an incredible collection of scientific equipment from simple weights, barometers, thermometers, and chronometers, all the way to an electron microscope and modern computers including a CRAY 2 supercomputer. Nearly every device you can thing of including the design of cranes used to build churches in ancient times was included. I had taken a large number of photos but unfortunately those were lost when my phone was stolen.
It's well worth the price of admission and is one of the museums included in the Paris Museum Pass.

James & Ximara P
Hallandale Beach, FL3 contributions
A gem!
Jul 2024 • Family
This is an amazing museum especially if you speak French and your family is interested in science. My 14 and 10-year-old boys had a blast because they like science and I could translate for them. The kids listened to a nice audio guide. I would say you need at least 3 hours to appreciate the immense value of this museum. The short videos near some of the displays are both in English and French and kids can learn about how the speed of light was calculated, how a microscope works, how Lavoisseur concluded the composition of water, etc. The exhibits about transportation, textiles, clocks, barometers, hygrometers, etc are beautifully displayed. You will learn a lot about the industrial revolution, the production of textiles, galvanization, steel production, etc. We liked the Lavoisseur lab, the pile of Volt, the pendulum of Foucault, and many more amazing displays. The glass exhibitions of Tiffany, Baccarat, Lalique, and Murano pieces are just beautiful. Kids will learn about the history of measuring volume, weight, pressure, laws of chemistry, X-rays, acceleration of particles, the development of computers, nuclear plants, calculators, geometry, etc, etc. In summary, this museum is not like the standard interactive science museum in the US, but it is totally worth it if your kids are passionate about science and you know some French. The museum is a gem, but unfortunately, most of its content is exclusively in French.
Written July 17, 2024

Are there certain times of day one can see the automata in motion?
Written March 3, 2018
Diana B
Northallerton, United Kingdom
31 contributions
As others have said certain of the automata can be made to work by pressing buttons close to their cases. The age and fragility of certain automata means that the museum doesn't allow visitors to see them all in action on demand. When we visited last in December 2017 there was a film running in the side room where most of the automata are located that showed each of them in action. I guess this has been created in attempt to address the frustrations of those of us who would love to watch them all in action. The museum runs various seminars and workshops all year round. I'm not sure if there are any that relate directly to the automata but that wouldn't surprise me. The programme is available via the museum's website. Some of the workshops offered for children are especially interesting; it is just a shame that I exceed the age limit for such activities!!
